Commentary.Commentary: So, Pakistan have a big task in their hands. They are way behind and they need their batsmen to step up and not throw their wickets away. England will want to make use of the last few overs and pick some wickets before Stumps. They hold all the cards at the moment and let's see how they go. Join us in a while for Pakistan's first innings.

Pakistan, on the other hand, were poor with the ball. They started well and then fell flat as they conceded freebies to Crawley and Buttler. By the end of Day 1, their shoulders dropped. On Day 2, they bowled well in the first session but since then, they looked out of sorts and were just waiting for the declaration. Overall, it was a disappointing performance from their bowlers.

That's it then! England declare after posting a huge score on the board. They will be mighty pleased after electing to bat first. All the credit has to be given to Crawley and Buttler though. The hosts were in trouble at one stage, before Crawley and Buttler joined hands. From thereon, it was all England. Crawley and Buttler stitched a 359-run partnership before Crawley fell for a magnificent 267. Buttler fell for 152 and Woakes and the lower order added a few valuable runs before Root declared. They are on top of this game and will hope to take a wicket or two before the end of play.

Post the Lunch break, England will look to add more runs to their tally and get a huge score on the board. Pakistan, on the other hand, will hope that they can pick up wickets and bowl out England. They are way behind in this game and need something special to make a comeback. Join us for the second session at 1440 local (1340 GMT) to find out what happens.

Pakistan, on the other hand, were disciplined but were not rewarded with any wickets. Abbas was the best bowler on show as he beat the bat quite a few times but was unlucky. He could have had a wicket but the third umpire overruled the decision. Naseem Shah has just come back into the attack and he has done decently while Shaheen was wayward.

A shortened session where not many runs were scored but England will be happy as they did not lose any wickets. Play started on time but there were a couple of rain interruptions which led to the Lunch being extended. Only 18 overs were bowled in the session but it was an engrossing one. Crawley and Buttler played cautiously and scored only 41, with the latter reaching his second Test ton. Crawley has struggled for timing a little and he will look to reach his milestone in the next session.

Day 1 belonged to England! It was a Crawley and Buttler show as they are in a middle of a 205-run stand and have put England on top. Zak Crawley is just 29 runs away from a terrific double century while Buttler is 13 runs away from reaching his ton. They will look to add some quick runs and take England to a total above 450 which will be a huge total on this wicket. Pakistan, on the other hand, looked tired by the end of Day 1 and sprayed runs all over and now they would hope that they can pick up wickets and bowl out England as soon as possible. It promises to be another exciting contest. Join us in a while.

On Day 2, England will look to continue to dominate and post a score above 500. They are scoring at a good pace and with the way, the partnership of Buttler and Crawley is going, it is highly possible that they will reach it before the end of the second session. Join us at 1100 local (1000 GMT) to find out what happens. Until then, cheers and take care.

Pakistan, on the other hand, were disappointing to say the least since they picked up the wicket of Pope. They bowled poor lines and lengths and gave away too many freebies. Yasir Shah bowled his heart out and was rewarded with 2 wickets but the others were not upto the mark.

Crawley was the star of the show but Buttler also has to be given credit. He came in when England were in a spot of bother. He took his time to settle in and then when he settled, he showed his vast range of shots. He is just 13 runs away from a century and will hope that he gets there on Day 2. Him, along with Crawley, have put England in a position of strength.

We are back for the final session of Day 1. The Pakistan players are out in the middle. Zak Crawley and Jos Buttler will resume their innings for England.
... Day 1, Session 3 ...

Now, after the break, England would look to consolidate and not lose many wickets. They would love to go to the end of Day 1 without any further loss of wickets. Pakistan, on the other hand, will look to pick up wickets quickly as they know, one wicket will bring the bowling all-rounders into the crease. An interesting final session of Day 1 awaits us. Join us at 1600 local (1500 GMT) for that.

Pakistan, on the other hand, started the session brilliantly. They picked up the wickets of Root and Pope at the start and bowled brilliantly. They were unable to do much with the ball since then and have given some easy runs. Yasir Shah has been the pick of the bowlers so far while the others too did decently. They found a few edges as well but they did not go to hand.

A shared session, one would feel! The first hour belonged to Pakistan while the last hour was clearly England's. The hosts though started well but were given a setback by Naseem Shah when Root fell. Pope could not last long as he was outfoxed by Yasir. Then, Buttler joined hands with Crawley and since then, they have played positively and registered a 50-run stand. They are looking comfortable at the crease and they would hope that they continue post the Tea break and get England to a good score. Crawley is unbeaten on 97 and he will look to get to a century once the game resumes.

We are back for the second session of Day 1. The Pakistan players stride out to the field and they are followed by Zak Crawley and Joe Root. Mohammad Abbas will start with the ball for the visitors. His figures read 6-0-17-0 so far.
... Day 1, Session 2 ...

For Pakistan, the bowlers had to bowl against a strong wind. The opening pair of Afridi and Abbas bowled tightly in the first few overs and it was Afridi who got the reward as he removed Burns once again. However, as soon as Crawley came, he came with intent and scored his runs quickly to push Pakistan on the back foot. However, Yasir got rid of Sibley to break the stand and did not allow England to run away with the honors of the session. Who will have the upper hand in the second essay? Join us at 1340 Local (1240 GMT) for that.

Root won an important toss this morning and elected to bat first. While when Burns fell early, Sibley along with Crawley added 61 runs with Crawley scoring a majority of the runs in the partnership. He scored briskly as well and took the attack to the opposition. However, Sibley was trapped in front of the wickets by Yasir Shah for 22. Crawley though is looking solid out in the middle along with his skipper Joe Root. The duo have added 18 and would look to continue doing the same in the next session.

An excellent session of cricket with both sides doing well! England would've been a bit happier if they still had Sibley out in the middle. Similarly, Pakistan would've loved a wicket too but they bowled tightly in the last few overs to keep Crawley wait for a while to get to his half ton, eventually getting there on the last ball before Lunch. One can say that the English batters went to the break without taking much risk towards the end as they had got a decent score in the session already.

He was made to wait for this but he didn't get too irritated and has got the milestone exactly the way he opened his account, i.e. with a boundary. WITH THAT IT IS LUNCH ON DAY 1.

Flatter and around off, Crawley is on the back foot to punch it towards mid off.

Like Root, after getting beaten, Crawley works this ball on the leg side to get to the other end.

Poor from Crawley! He could've easily left that alone but he has been in good nick so far so he goes after this fuller ball outside off without any foot movement. A hint of away movement as well. He looks to drive but misses.

Gets to the other end this time by gently forcing this good length ball on middle towards mid off. The fielder there was slow and the cry from the keeper of 'Come on, yar' was heard. Pakistan would love to bowl more balls to the new man on the crease.
Another play and a miss! This is again around off on a good length, Root pokes again to get beaten.
Ripper! Shortish and just outside off, Root is on the back foot to play at it but is beaten for the outside edge.
Short and outside off, Crawley punches it well but finds mid off. End of a successful over for Yasir and Pakistan.
Another full ball, pushed towards mid on.
Full and on middle, Crawley keeps it out.
The skipper is off the mark as the first ball he faces is short and wide outside off, he punches it to deep cover for a single.
Joe Root, the skipper, comes out to bat.

OUT! LBW! Three reds and Sibley has to go. England lose a review as well. Sibley looked troubled a bit against Yasir and he has got his man. Yasir tosses this up around off and middle, Sibley comes down the track and looks to slam it through the leg side but misses to get hit on the pads. A massive appeal follows and the umpire raises his finger after taking his sweet time. Sibley and Crawley get together and refer it upstairs. The replays roll in and the Ultra Edge detects no bat. And, it is three reds on the Ball Tracker so Sibley has to go. He takes a review along with him. Pakistan break the threatening stand.
Dom Sibley has been given out LBW! He has taken the review after consulting the umpire. The Ultra Edge shows no bat while the Ball Tracker shows all reds. Review gone.
Full and around middle, Sibley flicks it towards mid-wicket.
Firmly punched but straight to mid off. Another excellent over for England, 8 runs coming from it.
Full and around off again, Crawley watchfully defends it.
Fuller and around off, pushed towards the gully fielder.
A block to follow the two boundaries on this fuller ball.
FOUR! Yes, the runs are coming thick and fast. Naseem bowls it short and just outside off, Crawley goes back quickly and powers it through mid-wicket to bag another boundary.

FOUR! Nicely done! Fuller and outside off, Crawley allows the ball to come to him and then gently pushes at it. It goes through gully for another boundary. Runs coming nicely for the hosts. It was off the outside edge but gentle hands meant that it went along the ground.
Floated on middle and leg, Zak works it to the leg side for a single.
Looped up ball on middle, Crawley blocks it back to the bowler.
On the pads, Sibley tucks it to deep square leg for a single.
Tossed up ball on middle, Sibley comes down the track and drives it to mid on. They think of a single but decide against it.
Full and outside off, Crawley pushes it to long off for a single.
Tossed up on off, Crawley defends it to cover.
Outside off, not played at.
Good length ball on middle, Sibley blocks it off the back foot.

Three now! Full delivery outside off, Crawley leans forward and drives it through the extra cover region! 50-run partnership is up. This has been good from these two. They have looked good so far and will look to continue.
Good length ball outside off, Crawley lets it go to the keeper.
Good length ball on middle, Zak defends it out onto the pitch.
FOUR! Poor bowling! Good length ball on the pads, Crawley flicks it to the fine leg region for a boundary.
Floated on middle, Sibley flicks it to the deep mid-wicket region for a couple.
Driven through mid off by the batsman. The batsmen have run through for a single.
Shorter on off, Sibley drives it straight to mid off for a single.
Flatter one on middle, Dom defends it back to the bowler.
Flighted on middle, Sibley uses his feet and flicks it to deep mid-wicket for a couple.
Floated on off, Sibley pushes it to cover.
Very full and just outside off, Crawley keeps it out.
Goes full but this is on the pads, Sibley works it towards fine leg for a single.
Another one outside off on a good length, Sibley shoulders arms.
This is an easy leave as it is  fuller but wide outside off. This one goes straight in the mitts.

Another one little too wide outside off, left alone. Well, that wasn't as simple as it may sound. After going past the batsman, the ball comes back in and Rizwan had to dive a little to his left to collect.
Naseem begins his spell with a shortish ball outside off, Sibley lets it be.
Tossed up ball on middle, Sibley tucks it to mid-wicket for a single.
Flatter on off, Crawley pushes it to long off for a single.
FOUR! SMASHED! Crawley has made a good start and he needs to make full use of it! Short and outside off, Crawley thrashes it through the cover region for a boundary.
Looped up ball outside off, Crawley punches it to cover.
Tossed up outside off, Zak prods forward and pushes it to the fielder at mid off.
Floated on off, Crawley drives it back to the bowler.
Good length ball on middle, Zak works it to mid-wicket for a single.
On a length on off, Crawley looks to defend but it takes the outside edge and it goes through gully. Two taken before the fielder cuts it off.
Good length ball outside off, Crawley offers no shot to this one.
Good length ball outside off, Crawley shoulders arms to it.
Outside off, Zak lets it go to the keeper.
Good length ball on middle, Crawley defends it to mid-wicket.
Shorter and outside off, Crawley plays it to deep cover for a single.
Loopy ball on middle, Crawley defends it back to the bowler.
Floated outside off, Crawley rocks on his back foot and drives it through the cover-point region. Before the fielder can cut it off, the batters take two.
Short delivery outside off, Crawley punches it to cover.
Flatter one outside off, Sibley punches it through the cover region for a single.
Nicely played! Floated ball on middle, Sibley dances down the track and flicks it through mid-wicket for a couple.
Time for spin early in this innings as Yasir Shah has been brought into the attack.
Good length ball on off, Crawley blocks it to point for another dot.
Full delivery on middle, Zak works it to mid-wicket.
Too high! Nicely bowled! Good length ball on off, angling in. Crawley looks to defend but gets hit on the thigh pad. There is an appeal for LBW but nothing from the umpire.
Good length ball on middle, Crawley pushes it back to the bowler.
EDGY! Lucky for Crawley! Good length ball around off, Crawley comes down the pitch and looks to defend. It takes the edge and goes towards fine leg. A couple taken.
Good length ball on off, Sibley plays it to cover and takes a single.
This time he comes forward and blocks the fuller ball around off.

Oh! That was not too far away from the off stump. It is on the fuller length and just around off, comes back in but Crawley is confident that he is covering his stumps and shoulders arms. Any leave is a good leave if that is not scattering the wickets.
Fuller and outside off, Crawley looks to drive it towards the off side but the ball comes in a little late and that means it goes through mid off. A couple taken.
Outside off, left alone this time.
Around off, blocked.
Good length ball on off, Crawley prods forward and blocks it to cover.
Abbas dishes a full delivery outside off, Sibley shoulders arms to it.
Good length ball outside off, Dom watches the ball carefully and leaves it alone.
A single taken! Good batting! Full delivery on off, Crawley pushes it to cover and collects a single.
On a good length on middle, Crawley dances down and tucks it to mid-wicket.
BEATEN! That is an unplayable delivery from Abbas! Good carry to the keeper as well! Good length ball around off, moving away. Crawley looks to defend but it swings away and gets beaten.
Good length ball around off, pushed towards the cover fielder by Crawley.
Landed around middle on a good length, played back to the bowler.
Full and around off, this time Sibley is solid in defense.
Good length ball on middle and leg, Sibley tries to work it on the leg side but misses to get hit high on the thigh pad.
Shortish and around off, forced towards point by Sibley and a loud call of no for the run.
Ripper! Fuller and just around off, Sibley looks to defend but the ball swings away as it comes closer to the bat to beat the outside edge.
Another ball on the pads of Crawley, he powerfully works it through mid-wicket for 3 more. He moves to 11 in just 4 balls.
Outside off, not played at.
Good length ball outside off, Sibley leaves it alone.
BEATEN! Beautiful from Abbas! On a length outside off, Sibley looks to put bat on it but misses it altogether.
Hits the thigh pad! Brilliant delivery from Abbas! Good length ball around off, moving away. Sibley looks to defend but gets squared up. He gets beaten and gets hit on the thigh pads.
FOUR! Nicely played from Sibley! He is looking good so far! On a length on middle, Sibley flicks it to the deep square leg region for a boundary.
Good length ball outside off, Sibley leaves it alone.

FOUR! That was the magic ball but Crawley squirted it away through the slip cordon to get another boundary. Yorker around off, Crawley gets his bat down in time to dig it out and it goes through the cordon for another boundary. 9 runs off it but most importantly, a wicket for Pakistan.
Good leave! That was really close. Good length ball just outside off, Crawley covers his stumps and lets it be. More on the length than the line.
FOUR! Perfect way to get off the mark! A juicy full ball on middle and leg, Crawley whips it through mid-wicket and starts his innings with a boundary.
Zak Crawley makes his way out to the middle.

OUT! That has gone straight into the hands, feels the third umpire. The soft signal was out as well so nothing much for the third umpire to check. Shaheen Afridi has drawn the first blood and takes down Burns once again. Good length ball around off, Burns pokes at it but with hard hands. This time the ball takes a thick outside edge and goes to Shan Masood at fourth slip. He gets down and pouches the catch. Burns is not sure if that carried but Masood signals it's out. The umpires get together and refer it upstairs with soft signal being out. The replays confirm the same and Burns has to go.
Has that carried? Pakistan certainly thinks so! Burns is waiting as he is not too sure about that. The soft signal from the on-field umpire is out. Let's see what happens.
Good length ball on middle, Sibley looks to defend but the ball hits the upper part of the bat and goes to fine leg for a single.
Full and on middle, Sibley flicks it to the man at square leg.
Angled in from outside off on a shortish length, Sibley tucks it towards fine leg for a run.
Landed around off, blocked off the front foot.
Full and around off, pushed back to the bowler.
Slightly shortish and around off, Sibley plays it towards the off side off his back foot and calls for the single but Burns sees Fawad charging at the ball so sends him back.
Good length ball around off, guided towards the gully region with soft hands.
Good length ball on middle and leg, played towards the off side.
Way wide outside off on a fuller length. Goes past the batsman as he shoulders arms. The ball moves away a bit as Rizwan dives to his left to collect as the ball dies down.
Little wide outside off for Burns to play at that.
Fuller and around off, Sibley drives it past the cover fielder who chases it and keeps it down to one.
Outside off, left alone.
Landed fuller and around off, Sibley keeps it out.
Fullish and outside off, luring the batsman to go for the drive but Sibley is not interested as he lets it go to the keeper.
Good length ball around off and middle, Burns plays it back to the bowler with a solid defense.
Fullish and around off, Burns forces it towards point where Masood makes a diving stop to his left.
Little wide outside off, easy leave for Burns.

A couple for Burns. A good length ball around off, Burns tucks it behind square on the leg side. Naseem from fine leg was a bit slow in getting to the ball and that allowed the batters to return for the second run.
Sibley is up and running as well. Timed superbly! Full and on middle and leg, he whips it through mid-wicket and takes three before the fielder can chase and cut it off.
Play and a miss! Abbas is on the money right away! He starts his spell with a good length ball just outside off, Sibley plays at it away from his body to get beaten.
Mohammad Abbas will share the new ball from the other end.
Dot to end! Good start for both the sides. Good length ball just outside off, Burns first tries to play at it but hangs his bat in the end to allow it go to the keeper.
Good length ball just outside off, Burns lets it go to the keeper.
A muted appeal but nothing from the umpire. Good length ball on the pads, Burns looks to flick but misses and gets hit on the pads. There is an appeal made for LBW but the umpire shakes his head.
FOUR! First runs for England and Burns. He will be relieved! A good length ball outside off, Burns with soft hands runs it down through point and gully to bag a boundary.
Slightly short but outside off again, another leave by Burns.
Afridi starts with a good length ball just outside off, the ball moves away a hint as Burns shoulders arms.
We are all set to get underway! The Pakistan players make their way out to the middle, followed by Rory Burns and Dom Sibley. Shaheen Afridi will start with the ball.

Azhar Ali, the Pakistan skipper, says that they were looking to bat first as well as the track is looking good but adds the toss is never under control. Tells that they will look to utilize the conditions in this morning session. Reveals that they have not made any changes in the playing XI from the previous game. Feels all the bowlers are fit and fine and ready to go in this must-win game. Says every batsman wants runs under their belt and he is no different and would look to finish the series with runs under his name.

Joe Root, the England skipper, says that they will bat first. Adds that it is a bit dry and they will look to exploit it when they bowl later on. States that the wind is blowing and it is tough for the batsman. Goes onto say that they will look to put on a good score. States that they have made one change, Jofra Archer comes in for Sam Curran. Says that they want Archer to bowl short and fast spells.
Pakistan (Unchanged Playing XI) - Shan Masood, Abid Ali, Azhar Ali (C), Babar Azam, Asad Shafiq, Fawad Alam, Mohammad Rizwan (WK), Yasir Shah, Mohammad Abbas, Shaheen Afridi, Naseem Shah.
England (Playing XI) - Rory Burns, Dom Sibley, Zak Crawley, Joe Root (C), Ollie Pope, Jos Buttler (WK), Chris Woakes, Dom Bess, Jofra Archer (IN PLACE OF SAM CURRAN), Stuart Broad, James Anderson.
Toss - Up goes the coin and it lands in favour of England. They have chosen to bat.

Good news! The play can start 30 minutes earlier if there are any rain or bad light delays on Day 1. This is a great news as this will allow to make up for lost overs. The decision though will lie with the Match referee after looking at the forecast for the morning session.

A thriller in the first Test and a tame draw in the second encounter powered by rain and bad light, that's what we've got in this Test series. It is almost time for the third and final Test of the series. What's in store for this game? Well after the toss was delayed for a short time, we are all set to get underway. Will there be any changes in the personnel for this game? Will Anderson get to 600 Test wickets in this game or will we get to witness a Babar special? Too many questions. We will find the answers in the course of this game. Stay with us for the toss and team updates.

We are all set for the action to begin! The England players stride out to the middle. Azhar Ali strode out to the middle to open at the end of Day 3 but as the rules state that as the umpires had not called play, they are allowed to change the opening partners. Who are the openers for Pakistan? It is Shan Masood and Abid Ali, so Azhar Ali will bat at his regular position. James Anderson will start with the ball. The action begins on the other side.

Hello all! England continue to dominate the game and are on the verge of winning the series 2-0. They still lead by 310 and have forced Pakistan to bat again. Anderson is closing in on 600 wickets and would hope that he gets to the landmark soon. The hosts' fielding was a little poor during the latter stages of Day 3 and they would look to improve that. Pakistan, on the other hand, would be happy that Azhar Ali roared back to form with a scintillating century. They still have a long way to enforce a draw and they would need to perform exceptionally well to achieve it. The forecast is not ideal for Day 4 and Day 5 and the visitors will hope that it comes true and save them from the blushes.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

So end of another good day of cricket with a few rain interruptions. Pakistan have technically batted only once the whole day. From the situaton they were in, their skipper has given them a ray of hope of stealing a draw from this Test with the weather forecast not very ideal for Day 4 and Day 5, if you are a cricket fan or an England fan but the tourists will pray for rain. Join us on Monday, 24th August for Day 4 of the final Test between England and Pakistan. The action will begin at 1100 local (1000 GMT). We shall see you then. Till then, goodbye and take care!

There is all sorts of drama going on out there! The England players had made their way out to the middle. Azhar Ali and Shan Masood were going to be the openers for Pakistan but were sent back as the umpires are checking for the light and they have called STUMPS ON DAY 3.

Now, England would look to pick up a few wickets before the end of Day 3 while Pakistan, on the other hand, need a miracle to save them. They would desperately hope that the rain forecast comes good and help them enforce a draw.

Pakistan, on the other hand, rode on their skipper's knock of 141 and it is Azhar Ali who has given their side some respectability. They were stuttering early on in the innings but then Fawad Alam showed some resilience before he fell. Rizwan continued his good form as he played another solid knock of 53. Post his wicket, Pakistan faltered and were bowled out for 273.

ENGLAND HAVE ENFORCED THE FOLLOW-ON! Anderson leads his side out as he bowled brilliantly well to pick up a 5-fer. He could have had more if catches were not dropped off his bowling. England though have been terrific with the ball and they are fully ahead in the game. They still lead by 310 runs and they are holding all the cards at the moment. Anderson was the star of the show while he received good support from Broad and Bess. Archer and Woakes were off-colour.

OUT! CAUGHT! Finally, a catch is taken and Anderson gets his five-fer. 29th 5-fer in Tests! Brilliant stuff from Anderson! Good length ball outside off, Naseem looks to defend but it takes the outside edge and it goes to the third slip region where Sibley takes a good low catch. PAKISTAN HAVE BEEN BOWLED OUT FOR 273.
BEATEN! On a length on off, Naseem looks to defend but fails to get any bat on it.
Good length ball outside off, Naseem looks to defend but misses.
Good length ball outside off, Shah leaves it alone.
Outside off, Naseem sways away.
Length ball on leg and going away with the angle. Naseem looks to defend but misses and gets hit on the pads.
FOUR! Lovely shot but runs are not an issue and they will be happy to start the next over with Naseem Shah on strike! Short ball around off, Azhar whacks his pull to deep mid-wicket for a boundary.
Full outside off, Azhar swings but misses.
Fuller on off, Ali pushes it to mid on.
Back of a length on off, Azhar flat-bats it over extra cover and gets a couple as ideally they would like to deal in even numbers.
Back of a length ball on off, Ali gets behind it and defends it.
Short ball around off, Azhar pulls it to mid-wicket.
Jofra Archer comes back into the attack. 16-3-52-0 are his figures so far. Broad has gone off the field.
On the pads, Ali flicks it to the on side and gets a single.
Length ball on off, Azhar keeps it out.
On the stumps, Ali defends it.
On off, Ali blocks it.
Fuller on off, Azhar looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Good length ball on off, Azhar defends it.
On the stumps, Shah negotiates it.
Broad has been given a first official warning for running on the pitch.
Hopeful appeal more than anything. Good length ball outside off, Naseem looks to defend but misses. There is a hopeful appeal but the umpire turns it down.
On the pads, Azhar flicks it to the on side for one.
FOUR! Good shot from Azhar Ali! Fullish delivery around off, Azhar gets on his front foot and plays a lovely on-drive through mid on for a boundary.
Outside off, Azhar shoulders arms to it.
Down the leg side, Azhar looks to flick but misses. Again good take by Jos Buttler behind the stumps.
Naseem Shah is the last man in.

OUT! RUN OUT! That was absolute chaos! First a dropped catch but Abbas who was ball watching has not made his ground at the keeper's end. The frustration will not end though for Anderson! He has had three dropped catches off his bowling in his last two overs. England just one wicket away from bowling Pakistan out! Good length ball on middle, Ali pushes it uppishly towards mid on where Broad makes a mess of an easy catch. Ali who wants the single takes off but Abbas who is watching the ball is late to take off. Broad collects the ball and has a shy at the keeper's end and hits. No need for the third umpire as Abbas was well out of the crease. Broad apologizes to Anderson after that.
Good length ball on middle, Ali blocks it out. He would want to take a single now.
On a length on middle, defended out onto the pitch.
A single now! On a length on middle, Abbas looks to defend but it takes the inside edge and it goes to the deep square leg region. A single taken.
On a length on middle, Abbas flicks it to mid--wicket.
Full on middle, Abbas pushes it back to the bowler.
Full on middle, Ali flicks it to mid-wicket.

NOT OUT! Ali has just made his way in! He does not want to end his innings like that. Brilliant effort from Broad though! He bowls a good length ball on off, Ali looks to defend but it takes the inside edge onto the pads. He wants the single and takes off. Afridi obliges but seeing Broad charging in, Ali goes back. Broad collects the ball and throws it to the stumps at the keeper's end. The third umpire is called for and the replays show that Ali had made his way in.
A run out appeal has been taken upstairs! It looks close! Let's see what happens.
Full on middle, Azhar flicks it to mid-wicket.
FOUR! This is even better from Ali! Broad has lost his line a bit here! Good length ball outside off, Azhar drives it through the cover region for a boundary.
FOUR! Majestic shot from Azhar Ali! He continues on his merry way! Short ball on middle, Ali pulls it to the deep square leg region for a boundary.
Good length ball on middle, Ali flicks it to mid-wicket.
On the stumps, Abbas manages to block it. End of a very eventful over.

EDGED AND DROPPED AGAIN! Anderson cannot believe his luck and he must be fuming inside. Crawley is the culprit this time. Maybe Anderson does not have a 5-fer in his luck in this innings. Good length ball around off, Abbas has a poke at it but gets a thick outside edge which goes low to fourth slip. Crawley there gets both his hands to it but fails to grab onto it. The youngster has had such a good game so far but he fails to help his senior teammate add another 5-fer to his name.
On off, Ali plays to point and gets a single.

EDGED AND DROPPED! FOUR! Burns at second slip is the guilty party. Not his usual position as Stokes is the one who occupies that area generally. Good length ball on off, Azhar looks to drive but gets a thick outside edge which goes to the left of Burns at second slip. It is at a good height as well but he fails to hang on. The ball goes behind and they take a run. Anderson denied his 598th Test scalp and a 5-wicket haul. The ball goes behind and to the fence.
Down the leg side, Ali looks to flick but misses.
Full on off, Azhar taps it back to the bowler.
Down the leg side again. Buttler takes it nicely again but unlike Shaheen, Abbas does not get anything on the cherry.
Good length ball around off, Abbas defends it late from behind his body.
On the pads, Abbas looks to defend but misses and gets hit on the thigh pad.
Short ball around the body, Abbas ducks under it.
Length ball on off, Abbas blocks it.
Mohammad Abbas is the next man in.

OUT! Caught! Brilliant! Outstanding catch from Buttler! Wow! What a turnaround, in form Buttler has had, both with the bat and with the gloves behind the stumps. Broad bangs it in short around the body. Shaheen looks to glance it fine down the leg side. The ball kisses the edge and flies to the right of Buttler. He wears his Superman boots, flies to  that side and takes a superb one-handed stunner. England 2 wickets away now from wrapping up this innings.
Full ball on off, Ali pushes it to cover.
The batsman lets the ball go outside his off stump.

BIG SHOUT! England have burned all their reviews! Good length ball on middle, Ali looks to flick but he seems to have missed. There was a noise as it passed the bat. It hits him on the pads. Anderson appeals but the umpire shakes his head. The Ultra Edge shows that there was bat on it.

Full delivery on off, Ali pushes it to mid off.

Good length ball outside off, Ali shoulders arms to it.
Outside off, not played at.

Full delivery outside off, Afridi leaves it alone.

Full delivery outside off, Ali shoulders arms to it.

Good length ball on middle, Ali works it to mid-wicket.

Full delivery on off, Shaheen pushes it to point for a dot.

Afridi is off the mark! Good length ball on the pads, Afridi flicks it to the deep square leg region for a couple.
Shaheen Afridi makes his way out to the middle.

OUT! CAUGHT! The new ball does the trick for England! This is a good catch from Joe Root as it was travelling quickly. Broad gets his first wicket. Beautiful delivery from Broad and he fully deserves the wicket. Good length ball around off, moving away. Shah looks to defend but it bounces extra and it takes the outside edge. Back of a length ball on off, Shah defends it to cover off the back foot.

This is poor batting! Good length ball outside off, angles away. Shah looks to poke at it but misses it altogether.

Anderson bowls an out-swinger outside off, Shah leaves it alone.

On a length on middle, Shah tucks it to square leg.

Full delivery outside off, Ali leaves it alone. The ball wobbles after pitching and Buttler fails to collect it. He seems to have hurt himself but is fine to continue.

Full delivery on middle, Ali flicks it to mid-wicket.

Full delivery on middle, Yasir pushes it back to the bowler.

In the plain context of a session of a Test match, the post-Lunch session belonged to Pakistan but in terms of this game, England  are still well and truly on top. Pakistan lost Fawad Alam in this session but the skipper has led the fight and showed heart. Azhar Ali and Mohammad Rizwan, the last recognized batting pair, have done really well adding 83 runs and seeing out the session without any further damage. The skipper is 18 short of a well-deserved century but the tunnel is still dark in this Test match for the visitors. England will be satisfied if not too pleased with their efforts. They have plenty of runs to play with and would look to end this stand early in the final session and enter the tourists' tail. A tough session awaits Pakistan. Can they stage a big fight? Expect the unexpected from the mercurial Asian side. Join us at 1615 local (1515 GMT) for the final session to find out.

That's all from this game and series! England end up winning it 1-0 and it has been a terrific Test summer for them. All credit to Pakistan, they gave a tough fight in all the Test matches. Now, we move onto the T20I series which will be played at Old Trafford Manchester. The first T20I begins on 28th August, 2020 at 1800 local (1700 GMT). Join us for that. Until then, cheers.

England skipper, Joe Root says that he is happy with the boys for their performance and for the win. On what was said to Anderson, Root says that he said to enjoy and celebrate and adds Broad says some things and compared this coldy windy Wednesday night in the Premier League. On the young players, Root says Crawley's work ethic and reading of the game has been there to see and hence he is not surprised by his performance. Adds the way he played spin, seam was fantastic. Tells they knew they had to play well to win the series. Ends by thanking everyone involved in the series.

Pakistan skipper, Azhar Ali says that he regrets the final session of the first Test but congratulates England for winning the main session of the Test and playing good cricket. Adds they were good and were competitive and credits his biys for that. Tells there is always room for improvement but credits his bys for staying together and sticking together with each other and also for showing fight in the games. On his personal form, he says that it was important for himself and also for his side as they were in trouble. Adds that an innings like that can boast the confidence of any player

Pakistan's Man of the Series, Mohammad Rizwan says that he was practicing some drills before the series and that hepled him. States that he was told by his teammates that keeping is tough in England and he tried to practice it here and that worked. Says that it is difficult to stand near the stumps to Abbas but it has been nice to play in England. Goes onto say that he looked to play a compact innings and it is difficult to play with the tail but that is the beauty of Test cricket.

Player of the Series for England, Jos Buttler on Anderson, he says his variety and skills makes him stand out along with his longivety and adds he is an inspiration for all the boys in the dressing room.Adds it was a shame that there was no crowd to witness it. Says he was confident and kept his calm which is important in both succeess and failure. Tells nytime he can hit one past the bowler makes him feel like it is his day. Adds it was a good pitch and he was hapy to make a contribution. On Crawely and Pope, he says that thye have a good future and is excited to watch them bat. Adds Sibley and Burns also have a great future.  Admits he is happy to go out of the buble as it has been long and hard. Thanks the Pakistan side for coming to playin these tough situations.

Man of the Match, Zak Crawley, says that he cannot believe that he has the 10th highest score by and England player and says it is a huge honour. Tells that he was happy to get off to a start and ease the nerves and says he was happy to cash in on the start and get on a big score. Tells he had a very good preparation and he was preparing for these bowlers when he was out of the side. Says Stokes coming back in the side later on was not on his mind and when he got past 100 he wanted more. Tells it has not sunk in yet but he is sure that it will give him confidence.

England enforced the follow-on but rain had started to dominate and the pitch too had started to slow down and became flat like a biscuit. The openers took their time and with some luck built a 49-run stand. Azhar Ali then joined Abid and the pair did what they had to do, eat away the balls and ensure they get closer to rain. Abid's 162 balls 42 helped them get closer. Azhar Ali and Babar Azam then ensured there were no more damage at the end of Day 4 before rain came down heavily and killed all hopes of an England win on Day 5. The final day became more of a formality and about Anderson's unbelievable milestone which he got when he got rid of the Pakistan skipper. Asad failed to make the most of the formal day and got out to another low score before both sides decided that a result was not possible. Not much to talk about England's bowling. It was hard and they tried their best. Archer and Bess bowled their hearts out but to no success. Anderson got his 599th and 600th wicket while Root and Broad finished with one to their name.

Pakistan in reply got off to a terrible start and were staring at an innings defeat with the team struggling at 75/5 but the skipper, who was under tremendous pressure gave them hope along with Rizwan. The duo stitched together a 138-run stand and ate away a lot of deliveries. Azhar stayed unbeaten on 141, though that was not enough to avoid the follow-on but it was good enough to drag the game to days which had rain forecasted. The fine-wine, Anderson was the star for the England side as he finished with yet another 5-wicket haul. His partner-in-crime, Stuart Broad finished with 2 while Woakes and Bess had one apiece.

A little recap of this rain-marred Test, after winning the toss and opting to bat, England did not get off to a good start but a marathon 267 from Zak Crawley and a superb 152 from Buttler took the game away from the Asian side. The pair added a 359-run stand and took their side out of a danger position from 127/4. The hosts declared for a gigantic total of 583/8. It was a tough job for the bowlers with Mohammad Abbas going wicketless while the trio of Yasir Shah, Shaheen Afridi and Fawad Alam getting two. Asad Shafiq and Naseem Shah bagged one each.

That is it! The players are shaking hands and that is the end of the Test match and the series. It was another day marred by rain but this day will go down in history as Jimmy Anderson became the first-ever pace bowler to get to 600 wickets. A result was always unlikely after so much of the day being washed out by rain and wet outfield. England have won the series but with another draw, Pakistan add 13 points in their World Test Championship kitty.

OUT! There it is! A mountain no pace bowler has been able to scale before, Jimmy Anderson has scaled that as well. Welcome all! Pakistan had a good Day 4, losing only 2 wickets and now they have a realistic chance of saving this Test match. They were helped by rain as well and with the weather forecast not great for Day 5,  they would hope that they are able to achieve a draw. England, on the other hand, were poor with the ball. Will England be able to achieve a victory or will Pakistan manage a draw?

So that is it from Day 4 from Southampton. Pakistan will be the happier of the two sides at the end of the day's play as they now have a realistic chance to rescue this Test match. Anderson will have to sleep 1 shy of 600 Test wickets. The predicted weather forecast is not a pleasing one for all neutral and England fans but let's hope that rain stays away. Join us on Tuesday, 25th August, 2020 at 1100 local (1000 GMT) for the all-important 5th and final day of this Test and the series. Until then, cheers and take care.

A tough day for the English bowlers. The pitch did offer a little bit of movement early on in the day but after that there were hardly any demons on it. Anderson's hard luck continued as Buttler early in the day denied him his 599th scalp. Broad did manage to break the opening stand later on. With the ball getting softer and the pitch getting easier to bat on, the hosts' bowling struggled to get the breakthroughs. The 38-year old though finally managed to get to 599 wickets later on in the day but his wait for victim number 600 goes on. Tough day for all the bowlers in a nutshell as the pace has gone off the pitch.

STUMPS ON DAY 4! A very strong fight from Pakistan and with a very strong support from rain, the hosts have given themselves a very good chance of stealing a draw from this lost cause. They have lost just 2 wickets and will enter the final day with 8 wickets in hand. Shan Masood and Abid Ali started the day with a fighting stand of 49. The former was given a lifeline early in the innings by Jos Buttler who dropped a sitter. Though Masood did not score much, he did eat away 66 balls. Abid was then joined by his skipper and the pair fought on, playing some classical Test match cricket. Abid though became Anderson's 599th Test victim. The Pakistan Test skipper, Azhar Ali and the T20I skipper, Babar Azam then ensured there was no further damage before dark clouds and bad light came to the tourists' rescue.

TEA ALSO HAS BEEN TAKEN! That is a very good decision. We are hearing that 52 overs are left in the day and play can be extended till 1930 local (1830 GMT). Stay tuned.

Update 1510 local (1410 GMT) - Great news! The umpires have completed their latest inspection and we have a start time! The action will resume at 1545 local (1445 GMT), provided there is no further rain. The groundsmen have done an exceptional job to get the ground ready. Stay tuned.

Update 1456 local (1356 GMT) - More positive news coming in as most of the covers are off and the conditions have brightened up. There is still an area of concern though near the square of the pitch. Stay tuned.

Update 1425 local (1325 GMT) - The umpires are done with their inspection and they still are not happy with the ground conditions. There is another inspection scheduled at 1500 local (1400 GMT). Stay with us.

Update 1335 local (1235 GMT) - Good news! The rain has stopped for now but the ground has taken a lot of water and it will take some time to drain. The umpires have decided to have an inspection at 1420 local (1320 GMT). Stay tuned.

Update 1310 local (1210 GMT) - The Lunch break is over but it is absolutely pelting down in Southampton. It looks like we are in for a long delay. Let's hope that it clears soon and the players get back on the field. Stay with us for further updates.
... Day 4, Session 2 ...

England, on the other hand, were not upto the mark with the ball today. They did not bowl the perfect line and length and remain wicketless so far. Anderson could have had a wicket but Buttler dropped an easy chance of Masood. With the weather forecast not great, they will need to find breakthroughs sooner rather than later. Stay with us.

Update 1230 local (1130 GMT) - Early Lunch has been taken on Day 4. 18 overs were bowled in the session before rain forced the players off. Pakistan did really well in this session, not losing any wickets and batting sensibly. They have scored runs when available and respected the good deliveries. They would hope that they continue doing the same when the game resumes.

Update 1220 local (1120 GMT) - Another day and another rain interruption as it has started to rain and a bit heavily so the players are off. Pakistan have done well so far and have managed to have all their 10 wickets intact. They won't mind this rain and they will hope that it continues. England have not been good themselves this morning. As a neutral, let's hope that we can resume quickly.
